metadata.name: Multidimensional Maximalism #53
metadata.description:
Multidimensional Maximalism is my learning experience with layering and composition.

Using the Cellular Automaton algorithm from "Gen., Machina" we create multiple dimensions of life. Each with it's own unique evolution and structure. Like petri dishes in a lab. We then use different compositional elements to explore these dimensions.

100% code - as always.

Available overlays
--
* Lasers (drawing inspiration from The Harvest by Per Kristian Stoveland)
* Circleblend
* Drops
* Lenses
* Squares
* Crazysquares
* Waves
* Tesseract (drawing inspiration from the awesome Tesseract collection by Studio Yorktown)
* None (unlucky you)

Controls (in live view):
--
Press [1-9] to set the export scale ratio
Press [s] to save a high resolution image [ resolution x scale ]

enjoy.

metadata.name: Brinco #81
metadata.description:
As slinkies rise and sway through flurries of confetti, sometimes this play is focused and orderly. At other times, they crowd together riotously, conspiring to sneak off the sides altogether.

"Brinco" (Portuguese for "I play") is about celebrating finding joy in my creative pursuits again; about not overthinking it and simply following what makes me happy.

Creative joy can be capricious, leaving us when we need it the most. We hope we can relate to our artistic practice in a positive way, tapping into what feels like a bottomless source of energy and excitement. But sometimes when life becomes overwhelming, what gave you energy before now feels hollow and rote‚Äîjust one more thing sapping at you, and an emptiness where creative passion once resided.

For over a year, I've been sitting in this shadow. Until one day, I sat down and started tinkering‚Ä¶ and for the first time in such a long time, I started to feel the spark.

I hope that viewers and collectors feel that same spark of joy and playfulness when seeing these pieces that I've felt creating them.

Press "s"/"S" to save a PNG at the current size and press "h"/"H" to save a high resolution version.

metadata.name: Lands #47
metadata.description:
Lands are a group of artworks creating a minimalist and abstract satellite view. The earth is changing, more and more, day after day, the satellite views are a great proof of that. Stay aware and be careful is important.

I wanted to representing something real, linked with my values, and keep a beautiful composition and colors harmony.‚Ä® I worked with a new fresh touch for the colors management.

The size, position and frequency of the pieces are generated for each token, along with the color theme. 

Features : 
- piecesCount : the number of circles and rectangles.
- glitchLinesCount :  the number of lines behind the shapes.
- MultipleGlitchDirections : if the directions of the lines behind are just horizontal or vertical, or both (10% of chance to have only one direction)‚Ä®.

‚Ä®Handmade by code with Javascript, made with fragment.tools
‚Ä®Quentin Hocd√©, Brussels (Belgium), 2023.

metadata.name: Contraformas #104
metadata.description:
Shapes are drawn on a space-filling grid against other shapes, using a random walk algorithm. then they are separated with a random offset, hence the name counterforms (contraformas).

created by @mdollinger with p5js

metadata.name: The Great Annihilator #29
metadata.description:
One day you wake up,
All words are meaningless
And you can feel the light inside your mouth
Where everything were assembled and annihilated
Swallow the air, swallow all particle
A taste of burnt metal and ethyl
One thousand years of living souls
And you, are no more



=========

Controls:

[1] Set resolution to 716 x 1024px (default)

[2] Set resolution to 1433 x 2048px

[3] Set resolution to 2688 x 3840px

* The presets above are suitable for screen viewing up to 4k screen resolution. To set a custom resolution for printing and other purpose, add &res=[desired resolution] at the end of the URL. It will set the height of the image, and the width will be calculated automatically at 0.7 ratio. For example to get a resolution of 4911 x 7016px (about the size of A2 paper), add &res=7016 as URL parameter.

[c] Capture a screenshot at rendered resolution


Notes:

* This project use shaders that relies on GPU. Hi-res output may slow down your device. Since it also utilize GPU instance for thumbnail rendering, expect longer time for every iterations to be signed by fx(hash).

* If 'glitching' occurs or the composition behaves differently at different resolution, just refresh the page to reset it.

Made with cables.gl, a node-based webgl environment

XALTED 2023

metadata.name: D√©collage #39
metadata.description:
A generative sketch based on the concept of d√©collage, an artistic process that involves cutting or tearing pieces of an original image. The resulting outputs bear a resemblance to artworks produced using the lacerated poster technique, where posters are layered and torn to reveal parts of the posters underneath.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels. Note that this will not work with sizes beyond 5000 pixels.

(Allowlist is based on quantity of previous works owned).

metadata.name: Kinetograms #484
metadata.description:
Each Kinetogram traces the movement of a number of simple shapes constrained within a single cell or a grid of cells. Forces are applied to the shapes in the form of attraction, gravity or shaking.

Some Kinetograms are partially or completely reflected, vertically or horizontally, some with chromatic replacement.

The aspect ratio is 3:4. The palettes are predominantly based on found textile patterns.

Press 's' to save a png image. Press 'e' to redraw and export a 4K png image. Note that drawing and physical simulation takes some time.

For interactive use, press 't' to tilt the board and 'c' to clear the board.

Written in p5.js with 2D physical simulation using Matter.js. Developed in and optimized for Chrome.

metadata.name: The Spectrum Of Nature #154
metadata.description:
*\_../*`¬¨-‚Äô\/*`¬¨‚Äô‚Äô¬¨`*\/‚Äô-¬¨`*\.._/*

Nature, nature, evolving might‚Ä¶ Silent inventor, always right.
Where is the edge of nature and where do we begin?  
What is of nature and what is of man? 
Isn't everything made by nature's hands?

To know more about the concept and technicalities of this piece, see the fxtext article ‚ÄúThe spectrum of nature - a short making of‚Äù. Link at the bottom. If you‚Äôd rather just ignore my personal meaning, feel free to skip the article. 

\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\

Basic info:
The piece comes in possible portrait or landscape versions. Both have a relative size of 1 by 1.5. So the initial render will be 1000px wide and 1500px high for portrait. And 1500x1000 for landscape. With the ability to scale this up (see below).

The piece uses WebGL, so will perform much better with a graphics card. A faster computer will obviously be better, though I've done my very best to make it fast and efficient for any old laptop. My hope is that you will find the render process quick and enjoyable for the amount of detail that‚Äôs present. 

../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\..

Controls:
Press the [s] key to save the initial render. You will need to wait a few seconds after all the elements have stopped loading. A box will pop up in the top left saying ‚Äúdone‚Äù for 4 seconds when it‚Äôs ready. For the [s] key to work you may need to open in a new tab. But can right click save otherwise.

Larger sizes:
Press the [2-9] keys to save a resolution of that key size. So [2] saves a 2000x3000 size image, [9] saves a 9000x13500 size image etc. Unless you are making some very large prints you probably won‚Äôt need more than 4k (even 2-3k is big). Though the option is there. 

There may be slight variations in the textures for the larger renders, this is because the shader code has to redraw the textures at the higher pixel resolution, and getting the textures where they sit is more of an art than a science. All the elements remain exact however.

A palette creator by @nathansonic
Noisejs - github.com/josephg/noisejs - Perlin noise generator
Twgl - github.com/greggman/twgl.js - A small webGL helper.

metadata.name: SCHNEEWALD #120
metadata.description:
SCHNEEWALD is the second release in a row of about 12 tree/flower generative art works, which have come together over the last 10 years.

This project explores an approach to trees with snow using a recursive algorithm and includes Three traits: a density layer for the amount of trees and another layer for the amount snow and a third for how strong the branches bend.

Rendering progress indicated on the top left border
Press [s] in live view to download a high resolution png

Artist notes:
Since I moved to Wandlitz, north of Berlin, in the middle of the "Naturpark Barnim" (https://www.barnim-naturpark.de/), in 2003,
I've done a lot of exploring nearby nature. In addition to the beautiful lake and heath landscapes, I fell in love with the wild acacia forests. These strange trees, sometimes more like huge wild grasses, grow so wildly into each other.

I experienced it in all sorts of seasonal change, packed with snow is definitely among the most amazing! 

While playing around with different branching system code snippets, a more and more complex image composition came together. The final script for this project on fx(hash) was finally given more randomness for a wider range of different outputs and an additional random grain filter.

Project link: https://e-art.co/project/schneewald/

Many thanks to jesse (jbird) for the good collaboration, which ultimately made it possible to get this work released.
